00:48:04.530 --> 00:48:08.680 align:middle line:84%
About three months
after I was diagnosed,

00:48:08.680 --> 00:48:11.610 align:middle line:84%
I had decided I
wasn't doing chemo.

00:48:11.610 --> 00:48:13.792 align:middle line:84%
I'd decided I was
determined to live.

00:48:13.792 --> 00:48:15.000 align:middle line:90%
That's really important, too.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:16.650 align:middle line:90%
Because I asked myself--

00:48:16.650 --> 00:48:22.240 align:middle line:84%
someone challenged me and said,
do you really want to live?

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:24.300 align:middle line:90%
And I was like, I don't know.

00:48:24.300 --> 00:48:27.120 align:middle line:84%
I've never asked myself
that question before.

00:48:27.120 --> 00:48:28.250 align:middle line:90%
And I don't know if I do.

00:48:28.250 --> 00:48:30.720 align:middle line:84%
And I'm kind of scared,
what if I don't?

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:34.500 align:middle line:84%
I was scared to ask
myself that question.

00:48:34.500 --> 00:48:37.410 align:middle line:90%
And it was one of those--

00:48:37.410 --> 00:48:41.790 align:middle line:84%
this woman asked me-- this is
a natural health practitioner.

00:48:41.790 --> 00:48:42.930 align:middle line:90%
She asked me the question.

00:48:42.930 --> 00:48:46.020 align:middle line:84%
And then it was almost
like time froze.

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:48.750 align:middle line:90%
And I was in my head.

00:48:48.750 --> 00:48:56.220 align:middle line:84%
And I felt this fear of, like,
what if I secretly want to die?

00:48:56.220 --> 00:48:58.200 align:middle line:84%
And I realized that
my insecurities

00:48:58.200 --> 00:49:03.590 align:middle line:84%
and not loving myself and
really secretly hating myself--

00:49:03.590 --> 00:49:10.500 align:middle line:84%
that maybe my body was dying and
the cancer was a part of that.

00:49:10.500 --> 00:49:13.480 align:middle line:84%
Because maybe I secretly
didn't want to live.

00:49:13.480 --> 00:49:18.080 align:middle line:84%
But then I also had this
amazing epiphany, just in that--

00:49:18.080 --> 00:49:20.580 align:middle line:84%
you know how your
brain is firing, it's--

00:49:20.580 --> 00:49:22.242 align:middle line:90%
who knows how fast?

00:49:22.242 --> 00:49:24.450 align:middle line:84%
Your brain is like a computer
and all these thoughts,

00:49:24.450 --> 00:49:25.320 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE].

00:49:25.320 --> 00:49:27.000 align:middle line:84%
But then I realized,
wait a minute.

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:28.840 align:middle line:90%
I have a choice.

00:49:28.840 --> 00:49:31.260 align:middle line:90%
I can choose to live.

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:35.280 align:middle line:84%
And so I made the choice and
I said yes, I want to live.

00:49:35.280 --> 00:49:37.360 align:middle line:84%
I just-- OK, this
is just a choice.

00:49:37.360 --> 00:49:38.480 align:middle line:90%
It's a choice I can make.

00:49:38.480 --> 00:49:40.770 align:middle line:90%
My fate is not predetermined.

00:49:40.770 --> 00:49:43.140 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to make
this choice to live.

00:49:43.140 --> 00:49:47.580 align:middle line:84%
And so because I made
that choice to live,

00:49:47.580 --> 00:49:52.280 align:middle line:84%
then it made me start
thinking about the future.

00:49:52.280 --> 00:49:53.760 align:middle line:90%
OK, I'm going to live.

00:49:53.760 --> 00:49:55.510 align:middle line:84%
And I started making
plans for the future.

00:49:55.510 --> 00:49:58.958 align:middle line:84%
And so I thought, well what do
I want experience from life?

00:49:58.958 --> 00:50:00.000 align:middle line:90%
Well, I want to be a dad.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.940 align:middle line:90%


00:50:02.940 --> 00:50:05.550 align:middle line:84%
I want to know what
it's like to be a dad.

00:50:05.550 --> 00:50:06.360 align:middle line:90%
I'm 26.

00:50:06.360 --> 00:50:08.920 align:middle line:84%
I wasn't planning on
being a dad this soon.

00:50:08.920 --> 00:50:11.830 align:middle line:84%
But I also don't know how
much time I have to live.

00:50:11.830 --> 00:50:18.030 align:middle line:84%
And I wasn't certain I
was going to beat cancer.

00:50:18.030 --> 00:50:19.430 align:middle line:90%
But I wanted to start a family.

00:50:19.430 --> 00:50:22.920 align:middle line:84%
And so my wife and I had this
conversation just a few months

00:50:22.920 --> 00:50:24.000 align:middle line:90%
after I was diagnosed.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:29.700 align:middle line:84%
And we're talking about
maybe having kids and stuff.

00:50:29.700 --> 00:50:32.320 align:middle line:90%
And it was a delicate subject.

00:50:32.320 --> 00:50:38.940 align:middle line:84%
And I don't remember what I
said to her, but we talked.

00:50:38.940 --> 00:50:43.260 align:middle line:84%
And I said something
like, I don't know;

00:50:43.260 --> 00:50:45.540 align:middle line:90%
I want to start a family.

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:48.540 align:middle line:90%
And she did, too.

00:50:48.540 --> 00:50:57.540 align:middle line:84%
And she was, I feel like,
braver than me, saying yes

00:50:57.540 --> 00:51:01.140 align:middle line:84%
to have my child not
knowing if I was going to be

00:51:01.140 --> 00:51:02.640 align:middle line:90%
there to help her raise it.

00:51:02.640 --> 00:51:05.940 align:middle line:90%


00:51:05.940 --> 00:51:09.180 align:middle line:84%
And so we did the things
that people do when

00:51:09.180 --> 00:51:11.230 align:middle line:90%
they're trying to have a baby.

00:51:11.230 --> 00:51:13.420 align:middle line:90%
And she got pregnant right away.

00:51:13.420 --> 00:51:17.160 align:middle line:84%
And so one year after
I was diagnosed,

00:51:17.160 --> 00:51:21.120 align:middle line:84%
basically, we had
our first child.

00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:24.960 align:middle line:84%
And so I had even
more reason to live.

00:51:24.960 --> 00:51:31.920 align:middle line:84%
And I had this new infusion
of joy and purpose in my life.

00:51:31.920 --> 00:51:34.510 align:middle line:90%
And I think that was a big part.

00:51:34.510 --> 00:51:36.620 align:middle line:84%
I really think it
helped me in some way,

00:51:36.620 --> 00:51:38.120 align:middle line:84%
maybe a huge way,
maybe a small way.

00:51:38.120 --> 00:51:39.060 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:51:39.060 --> 00:51:43.350 align:middle line:84%
But just the fact that I was
bringing a baby into the world

00:51:43.350 --> 00:51:45.607 align:middle line:84%
and it was something that
I needed to take care of

00:51:45.607 --> 00:51:47.940 align:middle line:84%
and my wife needed take care
of and I needed to be there

00:51:47.940 --> 00:51:50.460 align:middle line:84%
for, I needed to
live for, it was just

00:51:50.460 --> 00:51:52.530 align:middle line:90%
another reason to live.

00:51:52.530 --> 00:51:58.920 align:middle line:84%
And so it's just amazing
to me that my wife

00:51:58.920 --> 00:52:03.330 align:middle line:84%
was willing to do that, that
she loved me so much that she

00:52:03.330 --> 00:52:05.430 align:middle line:90%
was willing to have my kid.

00:52:05.430 --> 00:52:07.740 align:middle line:84%
We had a beautiful baby
girl, healthy girl.

00:52:07.740 --> 00:52:14.100 align:middle line:84%
She's 11 now and she's just a
total tween, man, total tween.

00:52:14.100 --> 00:52:17.760 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, my wife
loved me so much

00:52:17.760 --> 00:52:21.870 align:middle line:84%
that she was willing
to take that huge risk.

00:52:21.870 --> 00:52:25.522 align:middle line:84%
And then we had another girl
about 3 and 1/2 years later.

00:52:25.522 --> 00:52:26.730 align:middle line:90%
And so now, I have two girls.

00:52:26.730 --> 00:52:28.840 align:middle line:90%
They're 8 and 11.

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:31.770 align:middle line:90%
And so yeah.

00:52:31.770 --> 00:52:33.820 align:middle line:90%
It's crazy to think about.

00:52:33.820 --> 00:52:36.930 align:middle line:84%
And it's funny
because we have two--

00:52:36.930 --> 00:52:40.500 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to throw
anyone under the bus here,

00:52:40.500 --> 00:52:44.370 align:middle line:90%
but there's my mom and her mom.

00:52:44.370 --> 00:52:48.360 align:middle line:84%
And one of the moms was very
excited when we told them.

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:50.640 align:middle line:90%
And the other mom was not.

00:52:50.640 --> 00:52:55.140 align:middle line:84%
The other mom was
like, well, don't you

00:52:55.140 --> 00:52:59.730 align:middle line:84%
think you probably should wait
till you're out of the woods?

00:52:59.730 --> 00:53:03.240 align:middle line:84%
And it was a little
bit like, really?

00:53:03.240 --> 00:53:06.450 align:middle line:90%
Thanks a lot for that.

00:53:06.450 --> 00:53:10.050 align:middle line:90%
But when is out of the woods?

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:12.030 align:middle line:90%
Was that five years from now?

00:53:12.030 --> 00:53:13.770 align:middle line:90%
What if I'm dead?

00:53:13.770 --> 00:53:16.637 align:middle line:90%
When is a good time to do this?

00:53:16.637 --> 00:53:17.470 align:middle line:90%
But it was too late.

00:53:17.470 --> 00:53:19.500 align:middle line:84%
She was pregnant,
so that's fine.

00:53:19.500 --> 00:53:21.370 align:middle line:84%
It's like, we're
having this baby.

00:53:21.370 --> 00:53:27.340 align:middle line:90%
But I'm just so glad I did.

00:53:27.340 --> 00:53:31.050 align:middle line:84%
If I had done
chemotherapy, it was very

00:53:31.050 --> 00:53:33.270 align:middle line:90%
likely I would've been sterile.

00:53:33.270 --> 00:53:36.570 align:middle line:84%
It's also very likely
I'd be dead today.

00:53:36.570 --> 00:53:39.955 align:middle line:84%
Because I've seen so many people
suffer and die after chemo when

00:53:39.955 --> 00:53:41.580 align:middle line:84%
they were made all
these promises that,

00:53:41.580 --> 00:53:45.690 align:middle line:84%
oh, you'll live longer or
we can beat this with chemo,

00:53:45.690 --> 00:53:47.350 align:middle line:90%
and this kind of thing.

00:53:47.350 --> 00:53:52.470 align:middle line:84%
I had a person very
close to me that

00:53:52.470 --> 00:53:57.280 align:middle line:84%
was diagnosed with the same
cancer I had, years after me.

00:53:57.280 --> 00:53:58.080 align:middle line:90%
It was stage IV.

00:53:58.080 --> 00:54:03.520 align:middle line:84%
And they told him, if
you do chemotherapy,

00:54:03.520 --> 00:54:06.760 align:middle line:84%
you'll probably live
one to two years.

00:54:06.760 --> 00:54:10.020 align:middle line:84%
If you don't do
chemotherapy, you're

00:54:10.020 --> 00:54:13.020 align:middle line:90%
going to die in six months.

00:54:13.020 --> 00:54:17.310 align:middle line:84%
And so if a doctor tells you one
to two years versus six months,

00:54:17.310 --> 00:54:19.800 align:middle line:90%
what are you going to pick?

00:54:19.800 --> 00:54:22.890 align:middle line:84%
And he didn't ask
me for any advice.

00:54:22.890 --> 00:54:26.420 align:middle line:84%
And he went with
the chemotherapy.

00:54:26.420 --> 00:54:31.940 align:middle line:84%
And he was dead in three
months, three months, man.

00:54:31.940 --> 00:54:38.083 align:middle line:84%
So I hear those kind of stories
all the time, all the time.

00:54:38.083 --> 00:54:42.110 align:middle line:84%
Patients are given this, chemo
will give you so much more life

00:54:42.110 --> 00:54:45.800 align:middle line:84%
and if you do nothing,
you're just a goner.

00:54:45.800 --> 00:54:47.450 align:middle line:84%
And then it never
works out that way.

